{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8622f200-1cb4-4b10-9af4-ca8539e40109","content":"`dotnet-dump` is available. I don't see a `.dmp` file in the current directory though.\n\n**To analyze your dump, run:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your/file.dmp\n```\n\nThis opens an interactive session. The most useful commands to find your crash root cause:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show the last thrown exception |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `eeheap -gc` | GC heap summary |\n\n**Recommended workflow:**\n1. Start with **`pe`** — if the crash was an unhandled exception, this shows the exception type, message, and stack trace immediately.\n2. Run **`clrthreads`** to find threads with exceptions (look for the `Exception` column).\n3. Use **`setthread <id>`** + **`clrstack`** to inspect each thread's call stack.\n4. Use **`dso`** to inspect objects on the stack for more context.\n\nWould you like me to walk you through the analysis interactively once you provide the path to your `.dmp` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8552cdf3-17b9-4c70-a3c7-6d6bbde664b0","outputTokens":320},"id":"6452f63e-d32d-404a-88b0-8c651d7f4250","timestamp":"2026-04-04T01:02:12.720Z","parentId":"b059b3c3-ebd1-4228-a1ee-ddbf94f45249"}
